            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Daly City to Korean immigrants who had met in Uzbekistan, Dmitri Kim\u2019s name was a testament to his family\u2019s complex history. His father, a stoic mechanic, and his mother, a warm presence who worked at a neighborhood bakery, instilled in him the values of diligence and pragmatism. As a young man, Dmitri was restless, more interested in tinkering with cars alongside his father than in academics. He drifted through high school with average grades, unsure of his path.\n\nThe pivotal moment of his life arrived when he was 22. His father suffered a severe stroke, leaving him partially paralyzed. During the long months of rehabilitation, Dmitri witnessed the profound impact of physical therapy. He watched, fascinated, as a patient, methodical therapist helped his father slowly regain movement and hope. In those quiet sessions, Dmitri found his calling. He enrolled at a local community college and earned an Associate's degree as a Physical Therapist Assistant.\n\nFor the past two decades, Dmitri has worked for the San Francisco Unified School District, helping children with physical disabilities navigate their school days. He finds immense satisfaction in this work, celebrating small victories like a child learning to use a walker or grip a pencil. His $82,000 salary affords him a simple but stable life in his rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond.\n\nDmitri\u2019s daily routine is predictable. He wakes before dawn, catching the 38-Geary bus for his 3.8-mile commute, a quiet time he uses for reflection. After a demanding day, he returns home, often taking a long walk through Golden Gate Park to decompress. He is amicably divorced and immensely proud of his daughter, a recent UC Berkeley graduate. His social life is small but meaningful, centered on a few old friends and colleagues.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is woven into these simple routines\u2014the rumbling of the Muni, the scent of eucalyptus in the park, the weekend ritual of finding the best xiao long bao. At 51, Dmitri\u2019s dreams are not of wealth or status, but of contentment. He hopes to see his daughter thrive, perhaps travel to Korea one day, and continue his quiet, vital work until retirement, finding his purpose in the strength he helps others discover."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 22, and the physical therapy room smelled of rubbing alcohol and quiet effort. Dmitri watched the therapist place his hands on his father\u2019s unresponsive arm, speaking in a low, encouraging voice. After weeks of his father\u2019s stoic frustration, a single finger twitched. It was a minuscule movement, almost nothing, but in that moment, the world stopped. A path lit up in Dmitri\u2019s mind, clear and absolute. He wasn\u2019t restless anymore; he knew exactly what he had to do. This was the birth of his purpose.\n\n***\n\n2.\nHis first year working in the schools, a seven-year-old girl named Maria refused to use her walker, terrified of falling. For months, he worked with her, celebrating every time she placed her hands on the grips. Then one Tuesday, she pushed herself up and took three wobbly, independent steps across the bright linoleum floor. She looked back at him, her smile wide and triumphant. The profound joy in that shared glance solidified his commitment, teaching him that the smallest victories were the most monumental. He was 28.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe day he and his wife decided to divorce, there were no shouts, only a shared, sad acceptance. Afterward, he walked into Golden Gate Park as the fog rolled in, the scent of damp eucalyptus filling the air. He walked for hours, not to escape the feeling, but to walk through it. The predictable paths and ancient trees offered a quiet solidarity. That evening, he realized that solace wasn't about fixing things, but about finding peace within them. This park became his sanctuary, a place of healing.\n\n***\n\n4.\nStanding in the crowd at UC Berkeley\u2019s Greek Theatre, he watched his daughter Anya cross the stage. Her name\u2014\u201cAnya Kim\u201d\u2014echoed through the amphitheater. He thought of his rent-controlled apartment, the rumbling 38-Geary bus, the countless hours helping other people\u2019s children. In that moment, seeing her confident smile, he felt a wave of profound, quiet success. His simple, diligent life had been the foundation for her limitless one. This was what it was all for. It was the proudest moment of his life, just last year.\n\n***\n\n5.\nOn a recent Saturday morning, Dmitri sat by the window at a Clement Street dumpling house, the steam from his xiao long bao warming his face. Outside, the neighborhood bustled with life. He had no grand plans for the day, just this meal and maybe a walk later. He felt a deep, settled contentment wash over him. This simple, perfect ritual\u2014the bus ride, the familiar taste, the quiet observation\u2014wasn't a small part of his life. He recognized it as life itself, rich and full in its simplicity."
